{{Infobox royalty |name = Shamsuddin Ahmad Shah |title = [[Sultan]] of [[Bengal]] |image = |caption = |succession = |reign =1433 - 1436 |coronation = |Full title = |predecessor = [[Jalaluddin Muhammad Shah]] |successor = [[Mahmud Shah of Bengal|Nasiruddin Mahmud Shah]] |regent = |spouses= |issue = |full name = |house = [[Ganesha dynasty]] |father = [[Jalaluddin Muhammad Shah]] |mother = |birth_name = |birth_date = 1419 |birth_place = |death_date = {{death year and age|1436|1419}} |death_place = |date of burial = |place of burial = |religion = [[Islam]] }} [[File:Dinajpur Rajbari (13).jpg|thumb|right|250px|Palace of Raja Shamsuddin in Dinajpur Rajbari.]] '''Shamsuddin Ahmad Shah''' (reigned: 1433–1436) was a ruler of [[Bengal]] and member of the [[Ganesha dynasty]]. He was the son and successor of Sultan [[Jalaluddin Muhammad Shah]]. After his father's death, he ascended the throne at the age of 14.<ref name=bpedia>{{cite book |last=Taher |first=MA |year=2012 |chapter=Shamsuddin Ahmad Shah |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Shamsuddin_Ahmad_Shah |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>
==History== Ahmad Shah ruled for only 3 years. His reign was marked with chaos and anarchy. According to [[Firishta]], he followed the liberal policy of his father and was known for justice and charity.<ref name=m4/> During his reign there was an invasion by [[Jaunpur Sultanate#Ibrahim Shah|Ibrahim Shah Sharqi]]. Later Ahmad Shah was killed by two powerful nobles, Sadi Khan and Nasir Khan in 1436AD.<ref name=bpedia /> After his assassination, Sadi Khan and Nasir Khan fell out with each other and were overthrown one after another. A descendant of the [[Ilyas Shahi dynasty]], ascended the throne under the title ''[[Nasiruddin Mahmud Shah]]'' in 1437.<ref name=m4>Majumdar, R.C. (ed.) (2006). ''The Delhi Sultanate'', Mumbai: Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan, p.211</ref>
